1383":"1345–1383","1335–1392":"1335–1392","1365–1413":"1365–1413","1372–Male":"1372–Deceased","1374–Male":"1374–Deceased","1308–1366":"1308–1366","1317–1381":"1317–1381","about 1360":"about 1360","1374":"1374","1372":"1372","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1392":"1392","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1345":"1345","1400":"1400","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1343":"1343","about 1345":"about 1345","after 1383":"after 1383","about 1365":"about 1365","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","London, London, England":"St Bartholomew by The Royal Exchange, London, England, United Kingdom","Cudham, Kent, England":"Cudham, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","London, England":"London, England","Bettreds Castle, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chaucer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: occupational name from Old French  <i>chaucier</i> ‘maker of  <i>chausses</i>’, an agent derivative of Old French  <i>chauces</i> ‘breeches, pantaloons, hose’. In 1484 these were ‘chauces of yron or legge harneys’ (   OED  ). Middle English  <i>chauce</i> was a general term for anything worn on the feet: boots, shoes, hose, or leggings. As Baldwin le Chaucer (1307   London Letter Books   B) was of  <i>Cordwanerstrete</i>, the early  <i>chaucer</i> was probably a worker in leather, a maker of leather breeches, boots, etc."],"variants":[{"name":"London Letter Books","meanings":["1  Scottish: locative name from Broats in Kirkpatrick-Fleming (Dumfriess).","2  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>bro(u)che</i> ‘pointed weapon or instrument; clasp, brooch, pin’, perhaps for one who made or sold such items. Compare Ralph Brocher, 1222 in   Feet of Fines   (Suffolk); John Brocher, Roger le Brochere, 1281 in   London Letter Books   B. Compare William Bruchemaker, 1381 in   Yorks Poll Tax   and William ploghbrocher, 1281 in   Fransson   (Lincs), probably a maker of ploughshares."]},{"name":"Causer","meanings":["English (West Midlands): probably a variant of <b>Chauser</b>, an occupational name for a maker of leggings or other apparel for the legs or feet, from an agent derivative probably of a northern variant of Old French <i>cauc(i)er</i>, <i>chaucier</i> ‘maker of hose, shoemaker’, although <i>Cauc(i)er</i>, the Norman and Picard form of the name, has not yet been noted in English medieval records. Alternatively, perhaps a variant of <b>Cosier</b>, an occupational name from Middle English <i>cosere</i> ‘horse dealer’."]},{"name":"OED","meanings":["1  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>jai</i>,  <i>jei</i>, occasionally  <i>gay</i> (Anglo-Norman French  <i>gay</i>, Parisian Old French  <i>geay</i>,  <i>jai</i>) ‘jay’, perhaps given to a chatterer, to someone absurdly dressed, or to a simpleton (see   OED  ).","2  English: relationship name from the unrecorded Middle English personal names * <i>Jay</i> or * <i>Gee</i>, which may have been pet forms of several names in  <i>J-</i>, such as   Jack  ,   James  , and   Jeffery   (Geoffrey). For a long vowel in  <i>Jeffery</i> compare Henry Jeeffery, 1685 in   IGI   (Folkestone, Kent).  See also  Jeacock  ,   Jakins  ,   Jason  , and   Jesson  ."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["equivalent of   Katherine  , also occasionally used in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Catherine Chaucer was born about 1345, in London, England, her father, John le Chaucer, was 39 and her mother, Agnes Copton, was 29. She married Simon Manning about 1360, in St Bartholomew by The Royal Exchange, London, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died after 1383, in Kent, England."},"et":{"about 1345–after 1383":"umbes 1345–pärast 1383","1343–1400":"1343–1400","1345–1383":"1345–1383","1335–1392":"1335–1392","1365–1413":"1365–1413","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1308–1366":"1308–1366","1317–1381":"1317–1381","about 1360":"umbes 1360","1374":"1374","1372":"1372","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1392":"1392","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1345":"1345","1400":"1400","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1343":"1343","about 1345":"umbes 1345","after 1383":"pärast 1383","about 1365":"umbes 1365","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","London, London, England":"St Bartholomew by The Royal Exchange, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cudham, Kent, England":"Cudham, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","London, England":"London, England","Bettreds Castle, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, Un